Why has ISIS been able to persist?
New York—İstanbul, Dhaka, and Baghdad's deadly terrorist attacks show that ISIS's reach has extended to Europe, North Africa, the Middle East, and Asia.
The longer ISIS remains strong in Syria and Iraq, the longer its terrorist network will carry out such mass killings.
But ISIS is not particularly difficult to eradicate.
The problem is that the countries involved in Iraq and Syria, including the United States and its allies, have not treated ISIS as their main enemy.
This should have changed.
ISIS has a small fighting force, with the United States estimating between 20,000 to 25,000 fighters in Iraq and Syria, and around 5,000 in Libya.
Compared to the active military forces of Syria (125,000), Iraq (271,500), Saudi Arabia (233,500), Turkey (510,600), and Iran (523,000), ISIS is nothing in comparison.
In September 2014, President Obama of the United States pledged to "defeat and ultimately destroy" ISIS, but the United States and its allies, including Saudi Arabia, Turkey, and Israel (in the background), have always focused on toppling President Bashar al-Assad in Syria.
Recently, Major General Herzi Halevy of the Israeli army bluntly stated (as reported by a journalist present at Halevy's speech to me): "Israel does not want to see the Syrian situation end with ISIS defeated, superpowers withdrawing from the region, and Israel facing stronger adversaries like Hezbollah and Iran."
Israel opposes ISIS, but Israel's greater concern is Iran behind Assad.
Assad allows Iran to support Israel's two major quasi-military adversaries — Hezbollah and Hamas.
Therefore, Israel's focus is on toppling Assad, rather than defeating ISIS.
Influenced by neoconservatism, for the United States, the Syrian war is a continuation of the global American hegemony plan proposed by Defense Secretary Richard Cheney and Deputy Secretary of State Paul Wolfowitz at the end of the Cold War.
In 1991, Wolfowitz told U.S. General Wesley Clark:
"But we (from the Gulf War) did learn one thing, that we can use force in the region — — in the Middle East — — and the Soviets will not stop us."
"Before the next superpower challenges us, we have about 5 to 10 years to clean up the old Soviet regimes — — Syria, Iran (as written), Iraq."
The United States' multiple wars in the Middle East — — Afghanistan, Iraq, Syria, Libya, etc. — — were to get the Soviets and later the Russians out of the competition, so that the United States could establish hegemony alone."
These "efforts" ended in complete failure.
For Saudi Arabia and for Israel, the main goal is to topple Assad in order to weaken Iran.
Syria is part of a large-scale proxy war between Shia Iran and Sunni Saudi Arabia, which has been fought in Syria and Yemen, and is also intensifying on the front lines of a more intense Shia-Sunni confrontation in Bahrain and other countries in the region with separatist tendencies (including Saudi Arabia itself).
For Turkey, toppling Assad would enhance its regional standing.
But Turkey now faces three adversaries along its southern border: Assad, ISIS, and nationalist Kurds.
So far, ISIS has been less important to Turkey than Assad and the Kurds.
But ISIS-inspired terrorist attacks in Turkey may change this situation.
Russia and Iran also pursue their own regional interests, achieving them through proxy wars and support for quasi-military operations.
But both countries have stated their willingness to cooperate with the United States in combating ISIS, and they can also collaborate on resolving other issues.
So far, the United States has remained indifferent, as its focus has been on toppling Assad.
The U.S. foreign policy establishment condemns Russian President Putin for shielding Assad, while Russia condemns the United States for attempting to overthrow Assad.
These complaints may appear to be directly opposing, but in reality, they are not.
The United States and its allies' attempts to overthrow Assad violated the UN Charter, while Russia's support for Assad aligns with Syria's right to self-defense under the Charter.
Admittedly, Assad is a tyrant, but the UN Charter does not grant any country the power to choose which tyrant to overthrow.
The persistent existence of ISIS highlights three major strategic flaws in American foreign policy, as well as a deadly tactical flaw.
First, the neoconservative demand to achieve American hegemony through regime change is not only a demonstration of bloody-minded ignorance; it is also classic imperial overreach.
Every place where the United States has attempted this has ended in failure.
Syria and Libya are the latest examples.
Second, the CIA has long armed and trained Sunni jihadists through secret operations funded by Saudi Arabia.
In turn, these jihadists gave rise to ISIS, which is the same direct (perhaps unexpected) consequence of the policy pursued by the CIA and its Saudi collaborators.
Third, the United States viewing Iran and Russia as irreconcilable enemies is to a large extent an outdated self-fulfilling prophecy.
Rebuilding relations with both countries is possible.
Fourth, at the tactical level, the United States' attempt to wage a dual war against Assad and ISIS has failed.
Whenever Assad is weakened, Sunni jihadists, including ISIS and the al-Nusira Front, will fill the vacuum.
If the United States, Russia, Saudi Arabia, and Iran provide air cover and logistics support, Assad and his Iraqi allies can defeat ISIS.
Indeed, Assad will continue to rule; indeed, Russia will remain an ally of Syria; indeed, Iran will gain influence there.
Terrorist attacks will undoubtedly continue, perhaps for some time still under the ISIS banner; but the organization will be driven out of its operational bases in Syria and Iraq.
This outcome would not only eradicate ISIS across the Middle East but also lay the foundation for a more comprehensive缓解 of regional tensions.
The United States and Russia can begin to reverse the recent new Cold War by jointly expelling jihadist terrorism.
(The NATO commitment to not admit Ukraine into the alliance or not escalate ballistic missile defense in Eastern Europe could also be beneficial.)
There are other benefits.
Adopting a cooperative approach to combat ISIS would provide Saudi Arabia and Turkey with reasons and opportunities to seek new pragmatic arrangements with Iran.
Israel's security can be strengthened by encouraging Iran to develop cooperative economic and geopolitical relations with the West, which in turn could increase the chances of a delayed but eventual peace between Israel and Palestine.
The rise of ISIS is a reflection of the current strategic shortcomings of the West — especially the United States.
The West is capable of defeating ISIS.
The question is whether the United States will undertake the necessary strategic reassessment to achieve this.
